There are two workable simple solutions if they were willing to work with the government people.  The woman said &quot;I don't show my face to strangers or unrelated males,&quot;.  Ok, female officer takes the photo, with most of the face showing leaving the veil also evident.  Then they make a note on the liscense about the fact that the person always wears a veil.  <br>
<br>
Seems to me that if there was a doubt that the veil-wearing person the officer stopped was not the holder of the card then they would need a female officer to come and look at her face to verify.  <br>
<br>
The easier solution would be to take the 'husbands permission' thing and have the husband simply 'allow' her to show her face to law-enforcement and military on request.  Most times they are going to take that veil off you anyway, with or without your permission if you are in the wrong.  May as well give her permission to let her off the hook regarding her religious obligations in those circumstances.  Since the husbands words overrides in that case anyway. <p><center><img src="http://cleric.homestead.com/files/mathi.jpg" border="0">
